Here's a minimal API endpoint that accepts multiple images plus a description field via `multipart/form-data`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (
    IFormFileCollection files,   // bound from all file parts
    HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the text field from the form
    var description = request.Form["description"].ToString();

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No files uploaded.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        // Validate content type
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var dest = Path.Combine("uploads", file.FileName);
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(dest);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(file.FileName);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, uploadedFiles = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()   // required for form posts without a token
.Accepts<IFormFileCollection>("multipart/form-data");

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **`MaxRequestBodySize`** — Kestrel defaults to ~30 MB; set it to 50 MB explicitly.
- **`IFormFileCollection`** — binds all file inputs regardless of field name.
- **`request.Form["description"]`** — reads the non-file text field from the same multipart form.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed in .NET 8+ since antiforgery is on by default for form-bound endpoints.

**Test with `curl`:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=My vacation photos" \
  -F "files=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "files=@photo2.png"
```

If you're behind a reverse proxy (IIS, Nginx), you'll also need to raise *its* request size limit (e.g., `client_max_body_size 50m;` in Nginx or `maxAllowedContentLength` in `web.config`).
